The `SkiaEntry` control maintains selection state:

```csharp
public class SkiaEntry : SkiaView
{
    private int _selectionStart;
    private int _selectionEnd;
    private int _cursorPosition;

    public int SelectionStart
    {
        get => Math.Min(_selectionStart, _selectionEnd);
    }

    public int SelectionLength
    {
        get => Math.Abs(_selectionEnd - _selectionStart);
    }

    public string SelectedText
    {
        get => Text.Substring(SelectionStart, SelectionLength);
    }

    protected override void OnPointerPressed(PointerEventArgs e)
    {
        _cursorPosition = GetCharacterIndexFromPoint(e.Position);

        if (!e.Modifiers.HasFlag(KeyModifiers.Shift))
        {
            // Start new selection
            _selectionStart = _selectionEnd = _cursorPosition;
        }
        else
        {
            // Extend existing selection
            _selectionEnd = _cursorPosition;
        }

        InvalidateVisual();
    }

    protected override void OnPointerMoved(PointerEventArgs e)
    {
        if (e.Buttons.HasFlag(PointerButton.Left))
        {
            _selectionEnd = GetCharacterIndexFromPoint(e.Position);
            _cursorPosition = _selectionEnd;
            InvalidateVisual();
        }
    }
}
```

## Character Index Mapping

Converting between screen coordinates and character indices is complex due to:

- **Proportional fonts**: Characters have different widths
- **Ligatures**: Multiple characters may render as single glyphs
- **Complex scripts**: Glyphs may reorder or combine
- **Bidirectional text**: Visual order differs from logical order

HarfBuzzSharp's cluster mapping provides the solution:

```csharp
private int GetCharacterIndexFromPoint(SKPoint point)
{
    // Get shaped glyph run from text cache
    var glyphRun = _textCache.GetGlyphRun(Text, Font);

    float x = point.X - TextStartX;
    float accumulatedWidth = 0;

    for (int i = 0; i < glyphRun.Glyphs.Length; i++)
    {
        var glyph = glyphRun.Glyphs[i];
        var glyphWidth = glyph.Advance;

        if (x < accumulatedWidth + glyphWidth / 2)
        {
            // Click is closer to this glyph's start
            return glyph.Cluster;  // Character index from HarfBuzz
        }

        accumulatedWidth += glyphWidth;
    }

    return Text.Length;  // Click after last character
}
```

The `Cluster` property from HarfBuzz maps each glyph back to its source character index, handling ligatures and complex scripts correctly.

## Selection Rendering

Selected text is rendered with a highlight background:

